  "response_text": "The cumulative mortality of the prey population initiates at zero and undergoes a rapid accumulation phase during the first approximately 500 time steps, reaching values exceeding 200 deaths. This initial surge reflects the combined impact of intrinsic mortality factors, including senescence onset at 7300 ticks and baseline internal mortality, alongside sustained hunting pressure from the 20 immortal foragers operating under dynamic optimal foraging constraints. The rate of mortality accumulation decelerates markedly after step 500, with notable inflections in the accumulation curve occurring around steps 362 and 1241, indicating demographic transitions as the initial population of 250 individuals becomes depleted.\n\nBetween steps 500 and 1200, mortality continues to increase but at substantially reduced rates, rising from approximately 200 to 237 deaths. This deceleration corresponds to declining herd densities that limit encounter rates with hunters and reduce density-dependent mortality risks. Significant structural changes in the mortality trend occur at approximately steps 625 and 850, suggesting punctuated shifts in population dynamics as the system responds to the two-year birth spacing interval (730 ticks) and variable food availability governed by seasonal grass regrowth cycles.\n\nFrom approximately step 1200 onward, cumulative mortality enters a plateau phase characterized by minimal net increase and oscillatory behavior with a dominant period of 63 ticks, potentially linked to seasonal resource fluctuations or reproductive cycles affecting prey vulnerability. The metric peaks at approximately 240 deaths near step 1876, subsequently stabilizing around 235 deaths by step 2312. The slight decreasing trend observed in the final analysis window (steps 1856-2087) suggests convergence across simulation replicates toward mortality equilibrium, where limited recruitment balances ongoing deaths, or the completion of extinction events in individual runs. The total cumulative mortality approaching the magnitude of the initial population indicates near-complete demographic turnover over the approximately 6.3-year simulation span, with hunting pressure and natural mortality collectively eliminating the equivalent of the founding herd before the system stabilizes."
}

